Analysis on Red Wines Quality by LINA TA

We are going to analyse a sample of red wines through their chemical properties and see which chemical properties determined their quality.

The mean is at 0.271g/dm3 The lowest level at 0g/dm3 while the highest is at 1g/dm^3 The distribution appears to be skewed to the right

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There is 1599 red wines tested in this dataset with 12 features ( fixed acidity, volatile aciditu, citric acidity, residual sugar, chlorides, free and total sulfure dioxide, density, pH, sulphate, alcohol and quality). The first 11 features are continuous numeric data. Only the quality is a discrete date ranging from 1 to 10.

Most of the red wines quality is ranked between 5 and 6. The mean fixed acidity level is at 8.32g/dm^3 The mean volatile acidity level is at 0.5278g/dm^3 For citric acid, it is interesting to notice that there are contain some pics at around 0, 0.25, 0.5g/dm^3 75% of the wines have residual sugar lower than 2.6g/dm^3 and are rather dry wines 75% pf the wines have chlorides lower than 0.09g/dm^3 For the sulfur dioxide and sulfate level, the data are slightly more dispersed which mean this might be a criteria of differentiation for the wines quality. The mean density is at 0.9967g/cm^3 quite similar to water The pH is almost normally distributed ranging from 2.74 to 4.01 which is a relatively normal range for red wines The sample’s alcohol range from 8.4% to 14.9%

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features of interest are the acidity (fixed, volatile, citric acid) and the sulfur content (volatile, total, sulfate added) and alcohol that might have a significative impact on the quality of the wine.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The other features such as residual sugar, chlorides, pH, density would also support my investigations since there are important criteria to judge the wines though the dataset seems rather homogeneous here

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I calculated the proportion of free sulfur dioxide on total as it is also a criteria of quality for the wines. The higher the proportion of free sulfur dioxide the more antioxydant content the wine have and will keep the wine better.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I mostly adjusted the binwidth in the different charts to better perceive the trend. Free sulfur dioxide and total sulfure dioxide were rather right skewed so i log-transformed these charts.

Correlation chart

Looking at the correlation matrix, it seems that alcohol, sulfates, citric acid and proportion of free sulfur dioxid have a positive correlation with the wine quality. While interestingly, total and free sulfur dioxide have a negative correlation with wine quality Another important factor is the volatile acidity which is negatively correlated with wine quality

Therefore, we are going to further analyse the impact of alcohol, volatile acidity, citric acid, sulfates and sulfur dioxide content on the wine quality.
One factor might influence another. There is a strong correlation between citric acid, sulfates and acidity I would have expected a correlation between sulfates and sulfur dioxide content since both act as an antimicrobial and antioxidant in the wine, but it is not the case.

Finally, it is notable that residual sugar have the lowest correlation with the wine here, the correlation p-value is not even significant. In fact, the residual sugar level is quite homogeneous in this dataset as we have seen in the univariate, most of the wines are dry, which might explain the low correlation here with the wine quality.

Acidity is good in wine, especially citric acidity gives a sensation of freshness But volatile acidity negatively impact the wine quality. We see also that pH is positively correlated with volatile acidity and negatively correlated with citric acid and quality. Though the correlation with the latter is very low.

We plot above charts to see the relation between pH, citric acid and volatile acidity. It seems that citric acid is used to correct the pH to give more freshness to the wine But wines with low citric acid have more volatile acidity and seems to drive the pH on the higher end Nevertheless, since pH have low correlation with the wine quality as it is in the “normal” average range for red wines, we might think that pH is a measure that winemakers have a target range but it is the type of acidity that make the difference for the tasting.

We saw a positive correlation between alcohol and pH at 0.2, but when we plot the chart it is difficult to draw any conclusion from that.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

Based on the dataset sample, red wine quality seems to be mainly determined by its level of alcohol, acidity type and level of sulphates. - Alcohol has the strongest relationship and seems to explain 22% of the quality variance - Volatile acidity is the second factor, explaining 15% of the quality variance. It is might one of the major criteria we taste to see if the red wine is turning to vinegar. - Citric acid positively enhance the taste of the wine and its quality rating - We found also a correlation with sulphates. Apart from the data description that say that sulphates play as an antimicrobial and anti-oxydant. We are not sure of the properties of the sulphates on wine. But it is interesting to see that its correlation with sulfur dioxide is very low, as the latter tend to negatively impact the wine quality.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

We found another interesting relation between pH, citric acid and volatile acidity. Though pH has low correlation with the wine quality here, citric acid is used to correct the pH and their relation are negative. While volatile acidity is correlated with higher pH and lower citric acid level.

It can be that there is a target range of pH in wine making but it is the type of acidity that make the difference for the tasting. There might be some chemical reaction factor that influence the type of acidity that depends on the winemaker know-how.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship found is alcohol.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

We made different classes of the wine quality rating: - [0,4] considered as poor quality - [4,6] considered as medium quality - [6,10] considered as good quality

When we plot the quality class as third parameter, it becomes quite apparent that good quality wines have the below characteristics: - alcohol degree higher than 10.42% (sample mean) - citric acid level higher than 0.271g / dm3 (sample mean) - volatile acidity lower than 0.5278g / dm3 (sample mean) - sulphates level higher than 0.271g / dm3 (sample mean)

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

As we saw in the univariate and bivariate analysis, we had the intuition that there might be a positive relation between the proportion of free sulfur dioxide on total and wine quality. - From the plot, the relation is indeed not as apparent. The distribution of good wines on the proportion axis are quite spread. - The observation is relatively the same for free sulfur dioxide’s multivariate plot. - However for the total sulfur dioxide’s multivariate plot, the result is more apparent. Good wines have a total sulfur dioxide generally lower than 46.47 g / dm3 (sample mean). - when we plot free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxid and quality, we can see no apparent trend.

Final Plots and Summary

Wine Quality distribution

We analysed here 1599 red wines under 11 differents criteria measuring their acidity, sugar, chloride, sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol and these wines have been rated between 0 and 10. We can observe than most of the wines are rated between 5 and 6.

Relation between alcohol, citric acid, volatile acidity and quality

From our analysis, we saw that the two majors determinants of wine quality are alcohol and acidity. Red wines with higher degree of alcohol, higher level of citric acid (between 0.42-0.75g/dm3) but lower level of volatile acidity are the highest rated here.

Relation between sulfur dioxid and wine quality

Finally the level of sulfur dioxid in the wine is also a determinant in qualty rating. Most of the good wines have total sulfur dioxid level lower than 46.47 g / dm3. We thought the level of free sulfur dioxid compared to bound can be an element of differentiation, but not in this sample. It is more the total sulfur dioxid level that counts.

Reflection

This was a very interesting project and dataset to analyse. Intuitively, I would not think that the alcohol level would be a determinant in the wine quality. Usually, we would judge at the taste including acidity, sweetness, flavors, the density, the odor. But the sweetness, density and pH did not have much impact on this sample.

From the univariate analysis, I tried to figure out the difference between free and bound sulfur dioxid and made the hypothesis that a higher proportion of free sulfur dioxide compared to bound would be better for the preservation of the wine and wine quality. But it seems that I was wrong. I couldn’t draw any conclusion from bivariates and multivariates analysis. However, it is clear that total sulfur dioxide from a certain level negatively impact the wine taste and wine quality.

It would be interesting to analyse further this dataset or bring more parameters to this analysis to understand what impact the alcohol level and why it is such a major component in this dataset.
